OK, film buffs are roasting perceived quality flaws. Animators are losing their jobs to AI. Both are valid complaints. On the other hand, the average viewer isn‚Äôt analyzing the number of wheels on the trucks or the oddity of a sloth in the snow. Was there an uproar in past years when polar bears popped open and drank bottles of Coke? No. Why? Because this is FANTASY. There isn‚Äôt a gigantic Santa propelling a soft drink caravan down the road. Lights don‚Äôt magically turn on when said caravan passes by. There are no drivers in the trucks. Did anyone consider that this bears a not-inconsiderable resemblance to an electric toy train of old? Lionel locomotives didn‚Äôt have engineers in them, and children often had to reposition errant cars on the track during their play time. What this DOES have is a catchy tune whose repetitive quality echoes the feel of ‚Äúreal‚Äù steam engines of the past ‚Äî both toy and life-size ‚Äî chugging along the railway. It‚Äôs an advertisement, not the Sistine Chapel ceiling. Does AI pose a threat to creative artists in a variety of fields? Absolutely. Is it fair to dump our upset about this technology on a 60-second video? Probably not.

0:16 Well this entire thing is bad, but as someone who is way too obsessed with penguins, what on earth is a baby emperor penguin (emperor penguins only live in Antarctica) doing with a gentoo penguin here? (Gentoo penguins live in the subarctic such as the Falkland Islands and parts of the Antarctic, and while technically penguins sometimes interact with other species, they‚Äôre still on the literal opposite side of the globe from polar bears. The animals it shows next are from places between the North Pole and Antarctica, so it would have made much more sense to show those first instead of teleporting to Antarctica then going back north.) Also, the sizes are wrong. Emperor penguins typically hatch around August (technically around 65 days after incubation, but that‚Äôs often August). Assuming this is in December, the penguin would be around 4 months old, which would make it almost as tall as its parents by then. Adult emperor penguins have an average height of around 122 centimeters/four feet, so the baby emperor penguin should just be a little below that. Gentoo penguins are typically around 70-90 centimeters/27-35 inches tall, so the baby emperor penguin should be taller if they were next to each other. Also, that one baby emperor penguin has a fluffy white stomach instead of just being gray. Emperor penguins don‚Äôt the white stomach until after they get their adult plumage, and after that they are more smooth/shiny feathers rather than the fluff that baby penguins have. And the other one has some black feathers and looks like it‚Äôs in the middle of getting it‚Äôs adult plumage, which they don‚Äôt get until being around 1 year old, while this one would have to be around 4 months old. And if it were old enough to be getting its adult plumage, it would DEFINITELY have to be taller than the gentoo penguin. Also, the white ‚Äúheadband‚Äù stripe on gentoo penguins doesn‚Äôt usually also have extra white splotches below the eyes or off to the side of the eyes. (Also AI is bad. Use real artists.)

‚Äã@Tayturscalling it "entirely stolen" oversimplifies things. Most models (like those powering Coke's ads) train on a mix of public domain, licensed, and user-generated data, not just copyrighted scraps. Recent rulings, like Getty's loss to Stability AI in UK court today, show courts rejecting blanket "theft" claims‚Äîit's more about fair use and licensing gaps, Anthropic just settled for $1.5B to cover works, proving companies are paying up where needed Coke's 2025 AI holiday ads? They're collaborating with AI agencies using tools that evolve with these fixes‚Äîthink upgraded nonhuman characters for that festive vibe, not some rogue, Every tech wave (photocopy to streaming) faced "overstep" cries, but it drove better rules. Using gen AI isn't enabling theft; it's pushing the industry to license fairly.
@NoahtheGameplayernot ‚Äújust‚Äù copyrighted stuff meaning it still does use it?

@kirapatatochips That's the core of the debate, isn't it? "Using it" is a loaded term. Think of it like a search engine. Google "uses" the entire internet, including copyrighted articles and images, to build its index. We don't call that theft because it's transformative. It creates something new‚Äîa map of information. AI models do something similar. They don't store a library of Getty images to reprint. They analyze patterns, styles, and concepts from a huge dataset (which yes, includes copyrighted works) to learn how to generate new, original content. The law calls this "transformative use," and it's a cornerstone of fair use. The lawsuits and settlements, like the Anthropic one I mentioned, are precisely about figuring out the licensing for that learning process. It's a new frontier, and the rules are being built in real-time. So saying it "still does use it" frames it as simple copying, when the reality is a much more complex, and legally defensible, process of learning and creation.

@xdddddd-q2y I get why it looks like that from the outside, but calling it "mediocrity and greed" misses the bigger picture of what's happening. Every major technological shift in creative tools gets called "mediocre" at first. The first CGI movies look laughable now. The first digital photos were grainy and worse than film. This is the awkward, experimental phase. Coke isn't saying this is the best art ever made; they're investing in and testing a new creative pipeline. And for a multi-billion dollar company, that's not just "greed"‚Äîit's strategy. They have to explore new tech or they end up like Kodak or Blockbuster. Using AI now is a calculated risk. It's cheaper, yes, which allows them to experiment and learn without betting the farm. They're paying to figure out the next frontier of advertising. So I'm not justifying the final product's quality. I'm recognizing that this is what innovation looks like in its early stages. It's a company using its resources to explore a new, controversial, and ultimately inevitable tool. It's less about justifying greed and more about identifying a technological shift in progress.

@stefankaiser3354 I completely understand your nostalgia for those classic, authentic Coca-Cola ads - there's something special about the tactile quality of film and those genuine human moments. But here's the thing: having $50 billion in sales doesn't mean they should only do what's always been done. In fact, companies with those resources have a responsibility to explore new creative frontiers, even if not everyone will love the results initially. Think of it this way: when digital photography emerged, many photographers swore by film. When CGI entered movies, people missed practical effects. But these technologies didn't eliminate the old methods - they expanded the creative toolkit. Coca-Cola can still make those classic Hollywood-style productions (and probably will for certain campaigns) while also experimenting with AI. It's not an either/or situation. They're diversifying their creative approach to reach different audiences in different ways. And who knows? Perhaps this AI experiment will lead to a hybrid approach that combines the best of both worlds - the efficiency of AI with the authenticity you're craving. Innovation needs space to breathe, even from the most traditional of brands.

I did 3D animation for ads for over a decade. Here is the truth: artists bring real ideas, early drafts look good, then the client says remove this, tone that down, make it like something else. Bit by bit the life is gone. What ships is the safest, dullest version of what we started. That is how the industry worked, and it still works. Now many big companies are going even cheaper with AI and templates. If you are an artist, be ready and adapt. Learn the tools, protect your voice on the projects you own, and walk away when a job turns into garbage. Crying will not help. Keep making the things you care about. Yes, it's just the start with AI and it's getting tuff. But it's here and won't go away just because people on the internet cry about it.
